@lindong28 's suggestion might require exposing the async callback in the KafkaSystemProducer: https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/SAMZA-1393
@jmakes @prateekm is what I said correct?

Any case I agree with @prateekm and that this PR makes this type of error handling simpler and we don't have to assume what the error handling behavior is for the underlying producer (which could change in future versions).

@prateekm and I discussed offline. Here is the summary:

1) There is no irrecoverable in KafkaProducer.

2) `SamzaLiKafkaSystemProducer.send(String source, OutgoingMessageEnvelope envelope)` sends message asynchronously and it does not provide way to tell caller whether a given message has been sent successfully. Thus we are using the `fatalException` to tell whether there has been any message send() failure. As long term solution, we need to improve this API design, probably similar to KafkaProducer's API, so that caller can tell whether any given message has been sent successfully. T

3) Due to the issue explained above, `SamzaLiKafkaSystemProducer` will fail persistently after one send() failure. Thus we need to re-instantiate producer after each failure. This is the approach adopted in this PR.

4) Another issue is that, currently `KafkaCheckpointManager` will retry using exponential backoff starting from 100 ms up to 10 sec per back-off. This means that up to 4 attempts can be made in the first second which seems too much. In general it seems simpler to just use the constant retry backoff similar to what KafkaProducer already does.

@shanthoosh Given the summary above, I would prefer that we go directly to implement the long term solution. But the short term solution as implemented in the current PR also seems OK. Due to the issue in 2) above, I don't think we should add retry logic in `SamzaLiKafkaSystemProducer` -- if we do so, caller may think the send() has succeeded even if the send() has failed.

